Kiba

Target IP: 10.10.33.231
New IP after reverting: 10.10.124.22

Scanning



There are three TCP ports open on the target machine as shown above from the nmap scans.

Enumeration

Port 5601: Kibana

The webpage above is displayed for this application. The target host has installed Kibana, an application which is used for data exploration.


Running whatweb against this port shows the target is running the version 6.5.4.


Doing a Google search for any vulnerabilities for this application version lead me to the interesting website above. Apparently this version of application is vulnerable to RCE.


I found a GitHub repository that contains the PoC on how to exploit the vulnerability.

Exploitation


I reverted the machine and it has an IP address of 10.10.124.22. I modified the payload above and replaced it my IP and port.


After, I started a listener on port 8443. I pressed the run button. Then, I pressed the Canvas feature to start the payload. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


Running /sbin/getcap / -r 2>/dev/null shows /home/kiba/.hackmeplease/python3 binary capabilities set.


And now I have a root shell.

Flags


The user.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the machine.


The root.txt flag once I used the misconfigured Python3 with capabilites set to spawn a root shell.
